Attack Flow Diagram
text
Victim visits compromised website
       │
       ▼
[index.html] sets session UID, creates hidden iframe
       │
       ▼
[frame.html] dynamically loads rce_loader.js
       │
       ▼
[rce_loader.js] extracts iOS version from User-Agent
       │
       ├──► iOS 18.4–18.5 → rce_module.js + rce_worker.js (CVE-2025-31277)
       └──► iOS 18.6+     → rce_module_18.6.js + rce_worker_18.6.js (CVE-2025-43529)
       │
       ▼
PAC Bypass (CVE-2026-20700)
       │
       ▼
Sandbox Escape → Kernel Privilege Escalation → Full Device Compromise
🔬 Research Directions & Discussion Topics
Code Research
addrof / fakeobj Primitives: Analyze type confusion vulnerability triggers and memory layout in JavaScriptCore

PAC Bypass Techniques: Study how CVE-2026-20700 bypasses Pointer Authentication via dyld interposing

Sandbox Escape Chain: Analyze the layered escape logic from WebContent → GPU → mediaplaybackd

Fileless Attack Techniques: Study how DarkSword executes entirely in memory without writing to disk

Setup & Reproduction Discussions
Offset Adaptation: Version and device-specific offset differences (iPhone 12/13/14/15) and adaptation methods

MTE Countermeasures: How MTE (Memory Tagging Extension) on iPhone 17 series and M5 chips blocks current exploitation methods

Stability Optimization: Improving trigger success rates in repeated testing

Detection & Defense: Identifying DarkSword attacks through traffic and memory signatures

Community Discussion Highlights
"Democratization" Risk: Does public exploit disclosure put nation-state capabilities in the hands of common criminals?

AI-Assisted Development: DarkSword's extensive comments and modular structure are considered highly consistent with AI-generated code

Supply Chain Security: Webpack source reconstruction and threat actor code obfuscation techniques

Defense Solutions: Community projects like AntiDarkSword have emerged as jailbreak tweaks to block such attacks

